## INSERT

Use `db.run()` with placeholders to avoid SQL injection.

```javascript
const newUser = { name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com', age: 30 };
db.run(
  'INSERT INTO users (name, email, age) VALUES (?, ?, ?)',
  [newUser.name, newUser.email, newUser.age],
  function(err) {
    if (err) console.error(err);
    else console.log(`Inserted with ID: ${this.lastID}`);
  }
);
```

Note: `this.lastID` gives the auto-generated ID.

## SELECT

- `db.get()` – returns the first row.
- `db.all()` – returns all rows.

```javascript
db.get('SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = ?', ['alice@example.com'], (err, row) => {
  if (err) console.error(err);
  else console.log('User:', row);
});

db.all('SELECT * FROM users', (err, rows) => {
  console.log('All users:', rows);
});
```

## UPDATE / DELETE

Use `db.run()` again.

```javascript
// Update
db.run('UPDATE users SET age = ? WHERE email = ?', [31, 'alice@example.com']);

// Delete
db.run('DELETE FROM users WHERE email = ?', ['alice@example.com']);
```

Always close the database when done (optional for scripts, but good practice):
```javascript
db.close((err) => { ... });
```
